text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!EndangeredLanguages]]%0a%0a!Mordvinic Languages%0a%0a:Author: dhrutik%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aMoksha and Erzya%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThe endangered language(s) I will be examining today are the Mordvinic languages, spoken mainly in western Mordovia, near Russia. These languages are mainly spoken in Mordovia, where the Mordvin people live. The Mordvin are split into two main ethnic groups: the Erzya and the Moksha. The languages of the Erzya and Moksha (the Mordvinic languages) are very different, so Russian has become a sort of common ground language between the two ethnic groups. Due to this, the knowledge of both languages has slowly been dying out. %0a%0aThere has been much effort from the Mordvins to pass legislation in attempts to preserve their language. For instance, At the Third Congress of the Mordvin People in 1999, there was a push to promote the study of Mordvinic languages in schools, however this was never actualized. This is one of the main causal factors for the endangerment of these languages: the fact that they are no longer taught in schools. Between this and the country’s national language being Russian, there is virtually no avenue for young children to learn the Mordvinic languages, and if this continues, the languages will slowly die out. %0a%0aCurrently, there are revitalization efforts as journalists make appeals regarding formal education of the languages to Vladimir Putin, whose responsibility as head of state is to “conduct a dialogue between representatives of different ethnic groups and religions.” If accepted, this could mean schools in this region will be required to teach Mordvinic languages, allowing for some hope that these languages will not be forgotten. %0a%0aSource: https://www.rferl.org/a/1078419.html%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210508-010215-221090#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Erzyan Music %0a-> - NickG%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0ahttps://youtu.be/eosqcOfjnec%0aThe above video is of someone singing an Erzyan song. The clothing worn by the singer in the first video is traditional clothing worn by Morodovian women dating back to the 18th century. %0a%0ahttps://youtu.be/kvHYusiQbLg%0aThis video is from the folk group "Merema," an Erzyan word meaning "a story, a legend," where this performance won them the "Best Authentic Band" award at the 2017 Russian World Music Awards. Since music is a powerful way of spreading a culture and a language, both of these musical groups contribute greatly to the revitalization of the Erzyan language in modern-day Russia. I think that the fact that a group like Merema can be recognized for their talent while singing a song in an endangered language shows that the Erzyan language, and Mordvinic languages in general, still have a strong community surrounding them.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-010215-221090#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: B:)%0a(:Category: EndangeredLanguages:)
